The noise in the background is my printer running, it never stops!
http://youtu.be/ZrPO8_jl2lg
http://youtu.be/u9x0sFstHQE

PLA 20%, .2 layer, 2 shells

The M5 nuts, .1 layer, 3 bottom layers, 4 top layers, and 4 shells.

I also printed the M5 bolts for early prototype, The design takes two of the reduction gear set and tthree 10mm sleeves.

Hardware List

12 VDC Motor
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B00BX54O8A/donscollecti

Assembly

I used a CAT6 connector to wire it up. The gear with the threads is off pitch by 15 degrees on purpose, it will thread onto M5 bolt fine, use a nut against the gear to secure it.

I included the drive coupler I'm using, which may not meet your projects needs, just adapt the other end to whatever you want.

description.text: Tasse

Here are two pots and a tray to keep the pot in. Each of these can be used individually or as any combination that suits your fancy. I have designed one pot smaller than the other with a specific intention. The smaller pot when placed inside the larger pot with a spacer at the bottom [ ideally in the centre where the drain should be] leaves enough space around it to pour a mixture that will set to form a pot, thus acting as a mould. Once the mixture hardens the two pots can be separated.

ps: I didn't put a drain in any of the designs because it was more practical to drill a hole that to close one in case it was not needed.

This enclosure is for Adafruit's Ice Clock kit which is available here:
https://www.adafruit.com/products/194

My wife disliked the bright blue color of this clock and the amount of ambient light that it produced at night. I designed this case to allow me to put any color of filter in front of the tube and change the color. I chose red since it's the same color as her alarm clock. The fit is snug but should work out fine unless you've soldered the tube in much differently than I have.

I printed my case with 50% fill. I printed the front face up and the back face up as well so there would be a nice finish on the exterior of the clock. The sides were printed bottom foot surface down. Front and sides were printed with supports.

Depending on your soldering, you may have to slightly move the end tube hole on the side of the case.

To mount the board into the case, I reused 2 of the plastic screws and nuts from the original plexiglass case. the one behind the power jack is a little challenging unless you have small fingers. I installed the screws with the head outside of the case and the nut toward the inside. I was able to squeeze my pinky finger into the back to hold the nut in place.

The case is held together by friction. My print turned out snug but not tight enough to break anything.

description.text: This is a thing for your SCRUM board: Print one for each team member and use them to fix the task tickets to the white board. Now everybody in the team knows who is working on which task. To make it, you will also need a magnet, I used these: http://www.magnete.com/en/discmagnets/0602.

If your team members have another name as "Holger" you will need to edit the scad file and change some parameters. I have left in the values I used to print names of different lengths, you can use these as starting points. If the result looks particularly ugly you can tweak the values in the arrays kern[] and scale[] to improve the results. (Change kern to shift the letters along the x-axis and change scale to change the x-size of a letter.) When you are satisfied, change the boolean "design" to false and render the result as two stl files (for multiple color printing). Uncomment the knobBody() or the knobText() calls in the last three lines of the scad script to to this. Use your favorite slicer to merge the stl files for your printer (I used my own version of RepRapPro's slicer: https://github.com/holgero/RepRapProSlicer with a layer height of 0.3 mm and 20% infill density. Last step: glue the magnet into the knob.

Have you ever put your glass on a coaster, and after a while when you try to take your glass again you also take the coaster with it? I hate that. So I designed my own coaster only thinking in how can I quickly drain the liquid off the base, so it can't do the 'sucker' effect on the coaster. This way liquid is drained to the external recess of the coaster and then retained there. Draining is optimised for low viscosity liquids, so don't expect it to work good on honey or ice cream. I opted here for cylindrical fluting, because it has better touch feel than other shapes like for example prisms, so its more comfortable to wash. I repeat I didn't think in its beauty, just funcionality. I don't think this thing is perfect, I call it 'perfect' as a joke, because maybe that is just convenient for my personal daily use.

Happy drinking with Perfster!!
Next I'll design the perfect cup!!!! :-)

This needed to be done! **

I've designed the board game in such a way that it neatly fits inside the slide lid box. Tolerances have been taken into account already so no extra adjustments needed.

The board is cut in 9 5x5 space squares, named in matrix form (a_{ij}) from 11 to 33, the "assembly" of which needs to match the board image here - tell me if you'd want them to have this matrix id on the actual piece.
The markings on the board are debossed, so you can "fill" them in with something like nail polish (the 3W, 2W, 3L and 2L as well as the center star)

When placing the pieces in the box, sandwich them between board pieces 25 at a time ( like in one of the images here) and then simply place the remaining boards on top of the others. The box will have a PERFECT FIT.

Since the letters are embossed, if your printer allows it, you can change the filament so that they stand out better (pause, change filament, resume printing).

I've also included a lid without the words "English version" if you want to print the pieces for a different language (the letters have the same values but a different distribution - google or search on wikipedia for the exact count), reason why all the letters are also uploaded individually.

title: Dual blower filament cooling fan mount for Folger Prusa i3 Dual Extruder

description.text: This is an addition to my Folger Prusa i3 Dual Extruder Conversion. It is a mount for blower fans to cool the filament for both extruders. The fans are 50mm blower fans and the mount sits on top of the extruder motors.

Once printed M3 nuts need to be pressed into the holes on the back of the mount. The blower fans should be bolted onto the mount with M3 bolts, snugly, but loose enough to adjust the angle. The blower ducts should be attached to each fan. The mount should sit on top of the extruder motors. Last, a thin zip tie must be threaded through the slot on the bottom of the mount on one side and threaded back up through the slot on the other side. Then take another zip tie and slide it over the loose pointed end until you have secured the tie snugly against the motors. Finally, clip the 2 loose zip ties to an appropriate length.
Wiring the fans is still a bit up in the air. I am using a Fan Extender (http://www.geeetech.com/wiki/index.php/Reprap_Ramps1.4_RRD_Fan_Extender) to run both my extruder motor cooling fans and the filament blower fans wiring each set in parallel. But I have run into some power consumption issues that cause my print jobs to crash when both extruders and all 4 fans are running. I still have to work that out and will update this when I figure out the correct wiring configuration.

description.text:
My first attempt at creating a 3d model of a molecule. I'd welcome some assistance in improving the build.

My build scenario

  • Makerfarm i3v 8" prussa
  • PLA (Gizmodorks)
  • Slic3r v1.29
  • Rectilinear detachable support, 3 interface layers with 2.5 mm spacing

Some history

Originally printed the model with support enabled which consistently resulted in failure. Then tried to add my own support similar to this thing which also resulted in failure. Diagnosed the problem to be supports not attaching to the bed well, hence the manual raft in the STL file. This addition, with support parameters mentioned above, resulted in the prints I have imaged. One of the hydrogen atoms detached from the support during print but the build was able to complete.

What I like

  • The build completed without a significant disaster
  • Supports came off with ease

What I don't like

  • I was lucky that only one part of the model fell off yet the build was able to complete.
  • A lot of support material is needed
  • too many aesthetic defects

I'm posting this in the hopes to get some suggestions from master builders. Please let me know if you have any ideas.

These are logotypes for "The OpenR/C Project". The original one is called "racing" and a never one is called "baseball". There are several formats available, if you need something, let me know!

title: Evolv DNA200 Box Mod - Box Battery - Dual 18650 (NO LiPo)

description.text:
This box mod work with Evolv DNA200 and two 18650.
The power is limited to 133w and u've to set 2S instead 3S in eScribe software.

This box mod is not easy to assemble.
Please be carefull and read FULL DNA200 datasheet before starting the job.
Choose accurately wire and battery contact.

I attach some version of the body with different connector / drip cap hole and different top look (flat or not flat).

Use the kind of battery contact u want. In my box mod i used:

  • spring from http://www.svapamo.it/;
  • drip cap easy flat 22 from http://www.svapiamo.com/
  • positive battery contact are Copper Sear Cap 1/4
  • wire 16 gauge (silicon wire);
  • magnets 3x2 and 3x1 (only for front panel).

Assembly steps in instructions.

If u need some different hole or different push button height simple ask me for it.

Youtube video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sUWxXvb31AM
Post in my blog: http://www.esigblog.com/evolv-dna200-box-mod-box-battery-stampante-3d
Good luck !

Update 29/08/2015
Re-upload all the body parts cause an error in STL.

I attached some picture with STEP 1 > STEP 11 and i describe here all the assembly phase.
Please read the DNA200 datasheet before starting the work.

STEP 1 = prepare the circuit and sold 4 long (silicon) wire to battery + and - and to GND and OUT (the GND go to the drip cap / 510 connector body [negative] and the OUT to the central pin of the connector [positive]).

STEP 2 = sold a bridge from battery - and GND of the balancing terminal.

STEP 3 = sold a wire from battery +. At the end u've to sold it to PIN 2 and 3 of the balancing terminal. I suggest to NOT sold at the same way of the STEP 2 because u've some thickness and after circuit will stand up.

STEP 4 = insert all the 4 long wire in the internal big hole.

STEP 5 = fix the DNA200 using M1.6 or M2 (5 mm long) screw.

STEP 6 = sold the positive contact OUT of the box (to avoid PLA/ABS damage !)

STEP 7 = sold the negative contact OUT of the box (to avoid PLA/ABS damage !)

STEP 8 = make a bridge of 36 mm (max 18 mm height) with a positive and a negative contact (spring).

STEP 9 = sold a wire to the bridge of step 8 and insert in the small hole at the end of the box.

STEP 10 = sold the wire of the STEP 3 (positive battery) to the PIN 2 and 3 of the balancing terminal.

STEP 11 = sold the wire of the STEP 9 to the PIN 1 of the balancing terminal. U can see two picture STEP_11: this because i did this connection two times to make the best and clean job but u can move the wire how u want.

STEP 12 =mount the display and fix it to the board using 2x biadhesive.

Of course u've to sold the GND and the OUT to your 510 connector / drip cap (!).

description.text:
After att total rebuild off my Turnout 32mm it's finally here.
Turnout for 45mm gauge tracks (SM45) common used in Garden railways (16mm and LGB scale).
The turnout radius are 1150mm and a steeper radius curved track is included .
I will be very glad if you publish pictures off your printings.

It should be easy to print, and it's around a total 10 hour print for one turnout.
Decide if you want to print left or right turnout and print one of each L or R part files . Part 5 are the same for both L or R.
All STL files has been tested in Netfabb.
I have printed my turnouts with PLA at 0.3mm layer height and 30% infill .
Part 4 STL:s are printed with 0.2mm layer height.
All files named dual_**** are for dual printing, files 4 and 5 are the same as normal printing.
